@node hunt "Module hunter in 1 kilobyte"

	@{b}Hunt v1.503@{ub}
	-----------

USAGE
	Hunt!

FUNCTION
	  Hunt! is a program  to hunt modules from chip mem. I wrote this
	because it can be possible that a large module ripper like exotic
	ripper can be loaded  over the module and make  it unable to rip.
	Hunt! is so small that overwrite is almost impossible to happen.

	Hunt! can recognize following module types:
	-------------------------------------------
	- Normal ProTracker modules
	- TFMX 4 channel and 7 channel modules
	- Pro Runner v1.0 modules

	  When Hunt!  finds a module  from mem it informs  user where it's
	located. Then use some  MemEditor to write that piece of memory to
	a disk. To be as small as  possible Hunt! doesn't include anything
	else than those recognition routines.

	  Hunt! can be stopped at any time  by pressing left mouse button.
	It also  detects the  size of chip mem  automaticly  and sets  the
	search range from $1000 to the end of chip mem area.

NOTES
	  As in every ripper, no check routine is perfect. Sometimes Hunt!
	offers data that just looks like a module.  Check the results with
	any memory editor.

@endnode

@node bfbplay "Small Protracker module player"

	@{b}BFBPlay v1.133@{ub}
	--------------

USAGE
	BFBPlay "MODULENAME"

FUNCTION
	  BFBPlay is a  *small* module player for those who  are short of
	chip mem. Player is less than 6kb  long so although you have A500
	with no fast  ram expansion you have a lot of chip mem free after
	this player.

	  BFBPlay won't take  any processor  time. Only time  goes to for
	interrupt routines that play the module,  but BFBPlay itself just
	waits until user closes the window.

	  Used playerroutine is v2.1a originally written by Peter Hanning
	from Mushroom  Studios. I fixed the  ancient DMAWait problem  and
	did some datamovements, so now the code doesn't store anything in
	its area.  It allocates  memory for that action.  I also did some
	fixes that make the player more reliable.

NOTES
	  My commandline parser in this player is ancient and it doesn't
	understand if you use quotes with  module names. If  your module
	name has spaces then just write the filename just like it should
	be, just without quotes. Parser will ignore extra spaces.

	  It's also  possible that for  example KingCON's  tabkey  option
	makes the module name different  than it should be and that's why
	BFBPlay's parser  doesn't recognize the module name.  Just remove
	the "tab" mark from the end of the commandline after pressing the
	tabkey. This should make this problem disappear.

@endnode

@node uncomment "Asm include optimizer"

	@{b}Uncomment v1.0@{ub}
	--------------

USAGE
	Uncomment SOURCEFILENAME TARGETFILENAME

FUNCTION
	  Uncomment is  meant to optimize assmebly include files. I wrote
	this when my  machine was  just a stock A1200 and the compilation
	of every assembly  program that used  intuition includes was very
	slow  and very memory  consuming.  For example by  optimizing the
	v3.1 intuition.i include file which is about 65kb long, you get a
	file which is just and just over 14kb. Optimization was over 50kb
	and the optimized file doesn't take so much memory to compile.

	  Uncomment  just rips comments and extra spaces out from include
	file. After the operation the  file is *very* unreadable,  but it
	doesn't  actually matter  because  compiler  can  still read  it.
	@{b}Remember to save the original includes!!@{ub}

NOTES
	  The command line  parser used  in this  program is very  lousy.
	You  are unable  to optimize  include files  which names  contain
	spaces.

	  You are not able to use same input and ouput filenames. This is
	to make sure you won't trash your includes. Although you optimize
	them and use the optimized versions, save the originals.

@endnode

@node mem "Small Memory indicator"

	@{b}Mem v1.0@{ub}
	--------

USAGE
	Mem [fontname.font] [fontsize]

FUNCTION
	  It opens a window  on screen where it displays  free chip, fast
	and additionally also the amount of current free  virtual memory.
	Numbers are  updated in every 1.5 seconds, so it is not consuming
	all of your processor time.

	  Mem uses topaz.font as default, but if you like you can make it
	to use your custom font also.  Font name is defined by giving its
	name  including the .font suffix. Size of the font cannot be over
	9 pixels, and if it is  not defined,  Mem will use size  eight as
	default.

	  Program can be easily  terminated by activating  the window and
	pressing escape key.  By pressing "s" key,  Mem will save a prefs
	file into  ENVARC: directory.  This prefs file contains  just the
	location of the indicator window. IE. You can move the window and
	save  it's  location to ensure that it will open  there after the
	next boot sequence, too.  (You have this program in your startup-
	sequence, right :)

	Example:
	--------
	Mem opal.font 9

NOTES
	  Diskfont.library must be available. Any version will do. Sources
	are also available in the sources drawer.

@endnode

@node blank "Screen blanker"

	@{b}Blank@{ub}
	-----

USAGE
	Blank [seconds]

FUNCTION
	  Blank  is a small  screen blanker  that waits until  user does
	nothing in a certain amount of time, and then blanks the screen.
	Interrupt routine is very  small and it's capable to detect disk
	drive, keyboard and mouse action.

	  Blank accepts one  number parameter from  command line telling
	how long it has to wait until it may blank the screen.  Max time
	is 999 seconds.  If there are no  parameters, the  default value
	is 120 (2 minutes). If you enter anything else than numbers, the
	value is simply ignored and default value is used instead.

	Example:
	--------
	Blank 360	; 360 seconds = 6 minutes

NOTES
	  Blank uses LoadView(NULL)  to load the black blanked screen. I
	have a feeling that this might interfere with some programs, but
	since I've not seen such program yet, I might just be imaging.

	  Sources are available in source drawer.

@endnode

@node uptime "System uptime indicator"

	@{b}UpTime@{ub}
	------
USAGE
	UpTime [boot]

FUNCTION
	  Uptime  tells you  how long  your  system  has been  up without
	reboots. I  wrote  this  sometime, because  I wanted  to make  my
	system be  more like UNIX is.  You know that  UNIX has a similiar
	command.

	  Uptime  tells you  you with  minutes, hours  and days.  Because
	uptime starts to calculate  time from the spot  when it was reset
	with the  'boot' parameter, it's reasonable  to add this command:
	'UpTime boot'  to your  startup-sequence.  By doing this,  Uptime
	resets itself in every boot sequence, and just by typing 'uptime'
	in the AmigaShell  you see how long  your system has been up from
	last reboot.

NOTES
	  Uptime calculates  current running time  from system clock  and
	that's why  this program  may not be  useful for those who hasn't
	got a realtime clock in their system.  This is because if you set
	the clock  again  then the result of UpTime is  no more valid. To
	prevent this,  you should reset the  Uptime every time you  reset
	your clock.  As you can see,  Uptime actually just  tells you how
	long yourr system has been up from last clock reset.

	  Sources are available in source drawer.

@endnode

@node grep "ASCII file string searcher"

	@{b}Grep@{ub}
	----
USAGE
	Grep FileName SearchString

FUNCTION
	  Grep searches any ascii string from the given file for you and
	prints it on the cli window. File is searched in 16kb blocks and
	lines that contain the "searchstring" more than once will not be
	displayed  more  than  once.  All  search  operations  are  case
	insensitive.

	  If you would like to find a string "BlizzMagic30.lha" from the
	aminet index you would type:

 	Grep "dh0:Aminetindex.txt" Blizzmagic30.lha

	  because the search is case insensitive, it's doesn't matter if
	you typed that line like this:

 	Grep "dh0:Aminetindex.txt" bliZZMAGiC30.lhA

	  Do NOT use quotes around the search string. If you type like
	this:

	Grep "dh0:aminetindex.txt" My search string

	  The grep will look for a string "My search string". If you use
	quotes around the search string, the search will absolutely fail.
	
	  I hope this makes some sence. :)

NOTES
	  All bytes that value below 32 are considered as line terminator
	codes, because they do not usually exist in plain ASCII files.
	Sources available.

@endnode

@node split "File Splitter"

	@{b}Split@{ub}
	-----

USAGE
	Split [-bBLOCKSIZE] inputfilename [outputfilename]

FUNCTION
	  Split splits large files into smaller pieces just like the Unix's
	split command. If you had a damn big lha archive that doesn't fit
	into one disk or two, then this command is made especially for you.
	Remember that the blocksize parameter is given as kilobytes.

	  To split a file named "foobar.lha" into for example 350kb pieces
	you would type:

	split -b350 foobar.lha myoutput

	  If the blocksize is not defined, then a default value will be used
	which is 500kb (=512000 bytes). Remember too, that a command "mulu.w"
	is used to parse the blocksize from the commandline. This prevents
	you from making larger than 65MB splits, but I think 65MB is enough
	for everyone.

	  Split adds a .000 suffix to the end of outputfilename. In our example
	above, the result files would be myoutput.000, myoutput.001 and so
	on until the whole file is splitted into pieces. If the outputfile
	name is not defined (a space is defined instead) then the outputfiles
	are named just .000, .001, .002 and so on until the whole file is
	splitted.

	  Sources available.

@endnode

@node bfbavail "Replacement for avail"

	@{b}BFBAvail@{ub}
	--------

USAGE
	BFBAvail [f]

FUNCTION
	  BFBAvail is a replacement for Commodore's "avail" command that
	does not work if you have more than 8 megabytes of memory. The
	command itself works, but it's unable to flush your memory if
	you have large amount of fastmemory. That's why BFBAvail was
	written.

	  The function is just like with the ordinary Avail command. Type
	BFBAvail and you see the amount of free memories including
	largest blocks and total sizes. As a bonus BFBAvail can detect
	and calculate the available virtual memory, too.

	  To use that flush option just type to the command line an "f"
	letter. Only the first mark is read, so it doesn't matter if you
	typed like this:

	 BFBAvail f

	of like this

	 BFBAvail flush

	the result is same. You memory is flushed.

NOTES
	  BFBAvail uses system flag MEMF_LARGEST to check out the largest
	block of each memory type. However, this flag is not defined
	under Kickstart 1.3 and below, so the output of BFBAvail may look
	a bit weird on those machines. That's now my fault though. Sources
	available.

@endnode

